\section{Electoral Losers and Experts: A Marriage of Convenience?}

Democracy rarely dies to the sound of tanks \parencite{Levitsky:2018aa}; it can also erode through legal reforms, independent commissions, and ``crisis cabinets'' staffed by experts \parencite{Levitsky2002}. In Finland, the COVID-19 pandemic made this tension especially visible: trust in public health authorities and scientific advisers was high on average, yet a subset of voters---disproportionately out-partisans---became more skeptical when expert guidance was delivered alongside the government's agenda. More broadly, research on democratic backsliding shows that in polarized electorates, citizens often tolerate illiberal moves when their side benefits \parencite{Svolik2020, Svolik2019}. Classic work links electoral competition and cleavage structure to regime vulnerability \parencite{Sartori1976, Dahl1971, Lipset1981}, while contemporary scholarship documents how incumbents tilt the field without canceling elections \parencite{Levitsky2010, Bermeo2016, Waldner2018} or how anti-elitism---a specific component of populist appeals---increases elite delegitimization and support for violating democratic principles \parencite{Lendway2025}. We push this literature one step earlier in the causal chain and ask: \emph{when do voters prefer the steady hand of experts over the rough justice of elections?} Our core claim is that technocratic delegation is ideologically valenced: when expert bodies are perceived as aligned with incumbents, electoral losers become less willing to shift authority away from elected politicians. In a way, we complement \textcite{VanderMeer2025} research, who find that rather than technocracy (or authoritarianism), dissatisfied democrats prefer direct democracy. In doing so, we advance the study of heterogeneities in support for expert delegation within the broader literature on losers' consent. 

We address this question by shifting attention from citizens' reactions to overt democratic violations to a prior and largely neglected choice: whether citizens are willing to delegate rule-making authority to unelected experts in the first place. We develop a simple voter-choice formal model in which individuals evaluate technocratic delegation in spatial terms by comparing expected policy outcomes under elected--politician control to expected policy outcomes under expert rule, where the latter depends on perceived government--expert alignment. The model implies that support for technocratic delegation is ideologically conditional rather than uniform. When expert bodies are perceived as aligned with the incumbent government, electoral losers become less willing to delegate as their ideological distance from the governing coalition increases; when experts are perceived as neutral, this distance penalty attenuates. We test these implications with a novel 2025 survey of adults in Finland---a high-capacity, multiparty parliamentary democracy and thus a hard case where expert governance might otherwise be broadly acceptable \parencite{OECD2021}. We measure ideological proximity to government with an individual-level, seat-weighted index based on party closeness, and we proxy perceived government--expert alignment through a relative trust gap between the Cabinet and the Bank of Finland. Consistent with our argument and theory, ideological distance depresses support for technocratic delegation primarily among respondents who infer that experts will follow the government's lead. In this way, the paper complements work on partisan tolerance of democratic transgressions (\emph{a la} \cite{Svolik2020, Svolik2019}) by identifying delegation to experts as an additional demand-side margin through which democratic accountability can be weakened.

Our contribution refines existing perspectives on democratic norms and losers' consent. While oppositions often support institutional checks as political insurance against executive overreach \parencite{Capoccia2007a}, we show that support for technocratic delegation depends on whether expert institutions are perceived as aligned with the incumbent governing coalition. This scope condition shifts the focus from aggregate trust in experts to partisan perceptions of government--expert alignment, helping explain why technocratic governance can polarize electoral losers even in high-trust democracies. Consistent with prior research, our results also fit a broader pattern of conditional democratic commitments \parencite{Saarinen2020}: some voters tolerate transgressions by ideologically congruent leaders \parencite{Saikkonen2022}, and preferences for expert decision-making concentrate among respondents who view ordinary citizens as less competent, whereas confidence in fellow citizens tilts preferences toward representative or participatory channels \parencite{Rapeli2023}.

Recent scholarship on polarization provides additional theoretical scaffolding for this argument, particularly once we distinguish ideological polarization (policy disagreement) from affective polarization (identity-based hostility toward opposing partisans). Affective polarization---the emotional dislike partisans hold toward supporters of opposing parties---has emerged as a strong predictor of democratic norm erosion \parencite{Foa2025}, as citizens increasingly evaluate institutional arrangements through a lens of partisan advantage rather than abstract procedural fairness. Crucially, this mechanism operates through identity-based reasoning, not only policy disagreement: voters may come to view political opponents as threats to shared governance \parencite{Gessler:2025}. In that context, expert institutions perceived as aligned with the incumbent coalition are readily interpreted as extensions of the opposing camp, which turns an ostensibly technocratic choice into a zero-sum partisan contest. This helps clarify why affective polarization may be especially relevant for technocratic delegation: unlike ideological polarization, which can sharpen policy disagreement without necessarily undermining institutional commitments, affective polarization directly corrodes willingness to cede authority to bodies perceived as captured \parencite{Orhan:2022}. Our finding that ideological distance depresses support for delegation among respondents who infer expert alignment is therefore consistent with a broader literature suggesting that partisan animus, not only policy disagreement, shapes willingness to trade democratic principles for partisan advantage \parencite{Simonovits:2022}.

Our account also complements two adjacent strands of research. First, when citizens perceive an ideologically congruent and competent executive, they may endorse reallocating authority in ways that weaken constraints because policy congruence and representation loom large---what \textcite{Singer2018} describes as the ``pernicious effects'' of good representation and performance on tolerance for constraining rival actors. Second, recent work emphasizes that democratic stability depends not only on losers' consent but also on winners' restraint, which often activates only as violations accumulate \parencite{Werner2025}. Our focus is on the losers' side of this equilibrium: when expert bodies are perceived as aligned with incumbents, ideological distance from government translates into lower willingness to delegate.

Finland provides a demanding test of this argument. It is a high-capacity, consensus-oriented polity where trust in public institutions and expertise is generally high. Precisely for that reason, it allows us to isolate heterogeneity in how citizens evaluate technocratic delegation. Our claim is not that Finns view experts as partisan in the aggregate, but rather that a subset of voters---especially those far from the governing coalition---infer alignment between expert institutions and the incumbent government when expert bodies advise, are appointed by, or implement the agenda of incumbents. In this framework, technocratic delegation is evaluated as a comparison between expected policy outcomes under elected politicians and expected policy outcomes under experts, where the latter depends on whether expert institutions are perceived as aligned with incumbents or insulated from them. Even in a high-trust environment, support for technocratic delegation declines with ideological distance from government when experts are perceived as government-aligned and attenuates when experts are seen as neutral. The observed pattern is therefore driven by heterogeneity within the electorate rather than by generalized anti-expert sentiment, situating the paper at the intersection of realist accounts of mass politics \parencite{Achen2016} and critiques of the administrative state \parencite{Hamburger2014, Glennon2014, Majone1994}.


\section{When Expertise Is Perceived as Partisan}

Democratic governance requires balancing technocratic delegation against democratic accountability. By technocratic delegation we mean the transfer of policy authority to experts or nominally non-partisan institutions insulated from direct electoral control, such as independent central banks, regulatory agencies, or constitutional courts staffed by specialists. Such arrangements are often defended as protections against partisan short-termism and electoral volatility, yet they necessarily trade off responsiveness to voters. In practice, delegating authority to experts may stabilize policymaking while reducing the public's direct role in decision-making \parencite{Caramani2017}. This tension is well established: technocratic policymaking can dilute traditional accountability because important decisions are made outside the arena of electoral competition and popular oversight \parencite{Bertsou2020}. Democratic accountability, by contrast, requires that those who make policy remain answerable to citizens through elections and representative institutions. The core problem, then, is political perception: what incumbents describe as neutral expertise, electoral losers may experience as unaccountable elite rule.

This problem is best understood within the broader logic of losers' consent. Democratic stability depends in part on losers accepting defeat while continuing to support the institutions that constrain winners, on the expectation that those same institutions will protect them in opposition \parencite{Pilet:2023}. Yet recent work raises doubts about how durable this reciprocal logic is under contemporary conditions. Citizens often evaluate checks and balances asymmetrically, valuing constraints most when they limit opponents and discounting them when they impede their own side \parencite{Arbatli:2021}. In that sense, support for institutional constraints may be strategic as much as principled. Our argument applies this insight to technocratic delegation. Electoral losers may support independent institutions in the abstract, but they withdraw support for delegation when expert bodies are perceived as aligned with incumbents. The issue is not opposition to expertise \emph{per se}; rather, delegation becomes politically costly when it appears to entrench the governing coalition's policy trajectory behind a veneer of neutrality. This conditionality helps explain how citizens can simultaneously endorse democracy, institutional independence, and expert competence while still conditioning their support for specific institutions on partisan expectations.

Institutional independence, however, does not automatically produce perceived neutrality. Preferences for technocratic delegation vary along non-ideological dimensions as well: attitudes toward technocracy track beliefs about mass competence, which helps explain why some citizens accept expert rule even in high-trust contexts \parencite{Rapeli2023}. Felt representation and partisan congruence can also legitimate authority shifts that sideline rivals \parencite{Singer2018}, while winners' vigilance tends to activate only as procedural violations accumulate \parencite{Werner2025}. These insights imply an important asymmetry: losers often read technocratic delegation through a partisan lens, while winners' support for constraints is more contingent and violation-sensitive. Even formally insulated institutions may therefore be ``independent but not indifferent.'' For example, the U.S. Federal Reserve has been described as a ``conditional inflation hawk'' whose choices can advantage one partisan bloc over another \parencite{Clarks2013}. For our purposes, the implication is direct: losers' consent to technocratic delegation depends on whether ostensibly neutral institutions are perceived as impartial or as aligned with the incumbent governing coalition. Oppositions may support checks as insurance against executive overreach \parencite{Capoccia2007a}, but a subset of voters will resist technocratic delegation when expert bodies are seen as government-aligned, even if they continue to support judicial or legislative oversight.

The same point can be restated more sharply in terms of democratic legitimacy. Losers' consent is easier to sustain when independent institutions are seen as credible guarantors of fair play \parencite{Anderson2005a}. Once those institutions are perceived as stacked with or sympathetic to incumbents, support for delegating authority to them declines. Technocratic delegation then appears not as neutral problem-solving but as a democratic end-run: unelected actors advancing the winners' program. Under those conditions, losers resist ceding authority and reassert the language of accountability and popular control.

This dynamic is amplified in polarized settings. In polarized polities, even nominally non-partisan institutions are interpreted through partisan lenses. Polarization erodes a shared baseline of institutional trust and increases the likelihood that courts, bureaucracies, and expert agencies are seen as favoring one camp over another \parencite{Paltra2025}. As \textcite{Svolik2019} argues, intense polarization ``undermines the public's ability to serve as a democratic check'' by encouraging voters to trade democratic principles for partisan gains. Empirically, support for liberal-democratic constraints has become increasingly sorted by partisanship: in countries governed by right-populist parties, government supporters express weaker support for constraints while opponents value them more \parencite{Claassen2025}. The key implication is not simply winner--loser asymmetry, but conditionality: winners discount constraints and losers champion them, unless losers come to believe that the institutions themselves are captured. Under such conditions, institutions designed to function as neutral referees can instead be seen as instruments of incumbent advantage, which corrodes their legitimacy \parencite[p.~471]{Lieberman2019}.

This account also helps bridge scholarship on technocracy, populism, and democratic representation. Populism and technocracy are often treated as opposing poles \parencite{Caramani2017}: the former valorizes rule by the people against elites, while the latter valorizes rule by experts against volatile mass preferences. Yet recent evidence suggests that citizens' orientations are more mixed than this dichotomy implies. Many voters combine populist and technocratic attitudes, endorsing expert involvement while rejecting party-mediated representation---a configuration sometimes described as ``technopopulism'' \parencite{Fernandez-Vazquez:2022}. Moreover, experience with populist parties in power appears to shape attitudes toward both populist and technocratic alternatives: when populist incumbents disappoint, some citizens become more favorable toward expert governance \parencite{VanderVeer2026}. Our theory exploits some heterogeneities within this literature. We do not argue that losers reject expert rule wholesale. Rather, support for technocratic delegation is conditional on perceived alignment. Electoral losers may be willing to delegate if expert institutions are credibly insulated, but they resist delegation when experts are perceived as aligned with the governing coalition. This is precisely the middle ground obscured by a simple populism-versus-technocracy dichotomy.

The same point extends to the literature on institutional legitimacy and democratic conceptions. Research on citizen understandings of democracy shows substantial heterogeneity in how representative, participatory, and technocratic models are interpreted and valued. Citizens with weakly crystallized liberal-democratic attitudes do not necessarily reject technocratic delegation; instead, support for democratic norms often varies with partisan advantage and perceived representation \parencite{Wunsch:2025}. This makes perceived expert independence central. Opposition to delegation among electoral losers need not reflect principled hostility to expertise; it may instead reflect inferences about whose interests experts will ultimately serve. This framing links our argument to broader work on institutional legitimacy, which emphasizes that citizen acceptance of unelected authority depends on perceived independence \parencite{Dellmuth:2019}, appointment transparency \parencite{Miliuviene:2024}, and cross-partisan confidence in neutrality \parencite{Angelou:2024}.

Given this theoretical background, our argument is straightforward. Electoral losers are most likely to oppose technocratic delegation when expert bodies carry ideological valence aligned with incumbents. By ideological valence we mean that expert institutions are \emph{perceived} as tilting toward one side of the political spectrum rather than operating neutrally. Expertise is never exercised in a vacuum: economic technocrats may adhere to market-liberal orthodoxies \parencite{Clarks2013,Clark2013}; legal and bureaucratic elites may share a regime's broader social outlook; scientific experts may prioritize values associated with one cultural camp. In polarized environments, such associations become politically salient. Losers may then come to view an ``independent'' central bank as effectively partisan or a court as stacked with loyalists. Decisions that appear technocratic on their face---public-health directives, monetary tightening, regulatory enforcement---are reinterpreted as partisan acts: technocratic delegation comes to look less like neutral expertise and more like entrenchment under the cover of objectivity.

Partisans also apply a double standard to nominally neutral oversight. Support for checks is strongest when they constrain the out-party and weakens when they bind co-partisans \parencite{Svolik2019, Kingzette2021}. This is consistent with realist accounts of mass politics, in which group identity and perceived representation often matter more than abstract procedural commitments \parencite{Achen2016}. Both winners and losers, in other words, can champion checks when useful and discount them when costly. From this perspective, demands for accountability may sometimes reflect outcome concerns rather than procedural commitments: ``unelected bureaucrats'' or ``activist judges'' become targets when they are perceived as aligned with the rival camp. Our contribution is to connect this demand-side asymmetry to technocratic delegation. Just as incumbents may erode checks to entrench power, oppositions may withdraw support from institutions they perceive as compromised.%, making commitment to rules contingent on who controls state authority \parencite{Waldner2018}.

The theory therefore points to two conditions under which resistance to technocratic delegation should be strongest. First, when polarization and partisan identity are strong, mutual mistrust is high and even independent institutions are easily coded as partisan. Under those conditions, the baseline for losers' consent---confidence that the system treats competing sides fairly---is weakened. Second, resistance should intensify when incumbents have politicized or captured nominally technocratic bodies. At the same time, our theory does not imply that electoral losers oppose expert rule in general. Support for technocratic delegation is conditional on perceived neutrality relative to partisan competition. This logic yields a clear empirical implication. Resistance to technocratic delegation should intensify in polarized and ideologically sorted systems, and especially during periods of sharp government--opposition conflict. The broader paradox is therefore political rather than institutional: bodies designed as impartial checks can support democratic stability only if they are \emph{seen} as impartial. Once they are perceived as instruments of those in power, the very actors whose consent matters most---electoral losers---may withdraw support.


%Where expert institutions enjoy cross-partisan trust, losers may delegate willingly; indeed, oppositions have at times strengthened independent authorities precisely to constrain executives \parencite{Keeper2003}. Likewise, citizens alienated from party politics (``structural losers'') may prefer technocratic governance to dysfunctional party competition \parencite{Bertsou2020}. These scenarios all depend on a credible separation between expertise and incumbent advantage. When that separation breaks down, technocratic delegation is no longer seen as a neutral solution but as a way to lock in the ruling coalition's program.



%Governments frequently use appointments and institutional reforms to bias independent agencies during episodes of democratic erosion \parencite{Luhrmann2019}. Once such moves become visible, they become focal points of conflict, and oppositions are more likely to resist further empowerment of those institutions.




% It also helps explain why populist movements---often composed of recent electoral or globalization losers---frequently target technocratic institutions as part of a corrupt establishment \parencite{Caramani2017}. Conversely, in consensus-oriented settings, or where expert institutions retain cross-partisan legitimacy, backlash should be weaker. 


\section{Spatial Policy Proximity under Perceived Government--Expert Alignment}

Consider a one-dimensional policy space $[0,1]$. A voter $i$ has ideal point $\theta_i \in [0,1]$. The governing coalition (``government'') has position $\theta_g \in [0,1]$. A technocratic institution (``experts'') has perceived position $\theta_e \in [0,1]$. Let $F(\cdot)$ denote the cumulative distribution of voter ideal points.

\paragraph{Distance and alignment.}

Define voter--government distance
\[
d_i \;\equiv\; |\theta_i - \theta_g| \in [0,1],
\]
which corresponds to our empirical measure \texttt{Government distance} (\autoref{eq:govdist}). Perceived expert \emph{alignment} with government is summarized by $\alpha \in [0,1]$ via
\[
\theta_e(\alpha) \;=\; \alpha\,\theta_g + (1-\alpha)\,\bar\theta,
\]
where $\bar\theta$ is a non-partisan reference point (e.g., a technocratic consensus or the median policy). Full alignment means $\alpha=1$ (so $\theta_e=\theta_g$); lower $\alpha$ implies more neutral experts.

\paragraph{Sequence.}

Voter $i$ chooses between retaining elected--politician control ($S$) and delegating authority to experts ($D$). Under $D$, policy is set at $\theta_e(\alpha)$.

%Before stating preferences, it is useful to clarify how this formalization maps onto the empirical strategy. Recent work on institutional legitimacy emphasizes that de jure independence does not necessarily translate into de facto independence or perceived neutrality, especially in polarized settings \parencite{Awawda:2024}. Citizens infer alignment through multiple channels---appointments, turnover, institutional outputs, and public conflict between governments and agencies. For that reason, our empirical proxy for perceived alignment does not ask respondents directly whether experts are ``captured,'' which would be vulnerable to wording effects and social desirability bias. Instead, we use a comparative trust measure (Cabinet trust minus Bank of Finland trust) as an indirect proxy for inferred alignment. This strategy is consistent with a behavioral account in which respondents who trust the Cabinet more infer that government-linked experts will track the Cabinet's priorities, whereas respondents who trust the Bank of Finland more infer a greater degree of institutional insulation. As we note below, this proxy is imperfect and may also capture generalized regime affect; the formal model nevertheless clarifies the specific mechanism we seek to test.

\paragraph{Preferences.}

Utility is spatial. Under the status quo ($S$), policy is implemented at $\theta_S$ (the policy associated with elected--politician control). Under delegation ($D$), policy is implemented at $\theta_e(\alpha)$:
\begin{align*}
U_i(S) &= -(\theta_i - \theta_S)^2,\\
U_i(D) &= -(\theta_i - \theta_e(\alpha))^2.
\end{align*}

Delegation thus affects utility only through the location of the implemented policy.

\paragraph{Indifferent voter.}

The indifferent voter satisfies $U_i(D)=U_i(S)$, which implies
\[
(\theta_i - \theta_e(\alpha))^2 = (\theta_i - \theta_S)^2.
\]
Hence, the cutoff voter is the midpoint between the delegated policy and the status quo:
\[
\theta_i^\star(\alpha)
=
\frac{\theta_e(\alpha)+\theta_S}{2}.
\]

Substituting for $\theta_e(\alpha)$ gives
\[
\theta_i^\star(\alpha)
=
\frac{\alpha\theta_g+(1-\alpha)\bar{\theta}+\theta_S}{2}.
\]

Delegation is adopted under simple majority rule if and only if
\[
\begin{cases}
 \dfrac{1}{2} > F\!\left(\theta_i^\star(\alpha)\right)
& \text{if } \theta_e(\alpha) > \theta_S, \\[8pt]
\dfrac{1}{2} < F\!\left(\theta_i^\star(\alpha)\right)
& \text{if } \theta_e(\alpha) < \theta_S.
\end{cases}
\]

Grafically,

\begin{itemize}
    \item Case $\theta_S<\theta_e(\alpha)$

