\end{figure}

\end{itemize}

\paragraph{When does an increase in $\alpha$ raise support for delegation?}

The answer depends on the relative location of the delegated policy and the status quo.

If $\theta_e(\alpha) > \theta_S$, voters with ideal points $\theta_i > \theta_i^\star(\alpha)$ support delegation. In this case, an increase in alignment raises support if and only if the indifferent voter shifts leftward:
\[
\frac{\partial \theta_i^\star(\alpha)}{\partial \alpha} < 0.
\]
Since
\[
\frac{\partial \theta_i^\star(\alpha)}{\partial \alpha}
=
\frac{1}{2}\big(\theta_g - \bar{\theta}\big),
\]
this occurs whenever
\[
\theta_g < \bar{\theta}.
\]
Intuitively, if the government lies to the left of the technocratic reference point, greater alignment shifts the delegated policy leftward. When the delegated policy is initially to the right of the status quo, this movement brings it closer to the electoral center and expands support for delegation.

Conversely, if $\theta_e(\alpha) < \theta_S$, voters with $\theta_i < \theta_i^\star(\alpha)$ support delegation. In this case, an increase in alignment raises support if and only if
\[
\frac{\partial \theta_i^\star(\alpha)}{\partial \alpha} > 0,
\]
which holds whenever
\[
\theta_g > \bar{\theta}.
\]
If the government lies to the right of the technocratic benchmark, greater alignment shifts the delegated policy rightward. When the delegated policy is initially to the left of the status quo, this movement brings it closer to the electoral center and increases support for delegation.

Taken together, these cases imply that alignment increases support for delegation precisely when it moves the delegated policy toward the side of the electorate that already prefers delegation relative to the status quo. When alignment instead pushes policy away from that side, support contracts.

The model yields two broader implications that map directly onto our empirical expectations.\footnote{The formal model is intended to clarify the mechanism and generate broad empirical implications rather than to identify every formal object directly in the data. In particular, quantities such as $\theta_S$, $\bar{\theta}$, and the exact comparative statics of $\alpha$ are not observed directly in our survey. Our empirical section therefore evaluates the model at the level of its central implication: support for technocratic delegation should decline with voter--government distance when expert institutions are perceived as aligned with the governing coalition, and this distance penalty should attenuate when experts are perceived as more neutral.} First, when expert institutions are perceived as highly aligned with the government (higher $\alpha$, so $\theta_e(\alpha)$ moves toward $\theta_g$), support for technocratic delegation becomes more tightly linked to voter--government distance: voters farther from the government's position are less likely to prefer delegation because the delegated policy is expected to track the government. Second, this distance penalty attenuates when experts are perceived as more neutral (lower $\alpha$, so $\theta_e(\alpha)$ moves toward $\bar{\theta}$), because delegation is then evaluated less as an extension of the governing coalition and more as a spatial comparison between $\theta_e(\alpha)$ and the status quo $\theta_S$.

% \paragraph{Mechanism and alternative explanations.} The model assumes that voters compare expected policy outcomes under alternative governance arrangements. Several alternative mechanisms could also generate a negative association between ideological distance and support for technocratic delegation. First, respondents might reject delegation because of generalized distrust in government and government-linked institutions, irrespective of expected policy outcomes. Second, some voters may hold a broadly populist rejection of expert rule, treating technocratic delegation as inherently illegitimate rather than conditionally acceptable \parencite{Caramani2017}. Third, respondents farther from government may have less exposure to, or familiarity with, state institutions and expert agencies, producing skepticism through distance from institutions rather than spatial policy expectations.

% Our empirical strategy cannot fully adjudicate among these mechanisms, but the interaction analysis provides leverage. Specifically, the negative effect of government distance appears primarily when respondents infer that experts are government-aligned, and it attenuates when experts are perceived as more independent. This pattern is consistent with the spatial mechanism and less consistent with accounts based on generalized distrust or uniform populist rejection, which would predict a distance penalty regardless of perceived alignment. At the same time, our operationalization of perceived alignment through a trust differential is necessarily indirect. Future work should therefore collect direct measures of whether respondents expect experts to follow government preferences, combine these with measures of appointment legitimacy, and use experimental designs that manipulate both appointment transparency and partisan cues to better isolate the spatial mechanism from alternatives rooted in identity-protective cognition or populist orientation.


\section{Data and Findings}

The data come from an original survey conducted in Finland ($n = \Sexpr{formatC(as.numeric(nrow(dat.t)), format = "d", big.mark = ",")}$), with statistical quotas for age, gender, and region of residence.\footnote{Data collection took place between \Sexpr{paste(fieldwork_months_txt, fieldwork_year_txt)} through an online panel recruited by Qualtrics. This study complied with standard ethical guidelines for survey research, including informed consent and respondent anonymity; data collection followed the ethical infrastructure and data-protection practices of \fbox{\phantom{\AA bo Akademi}} University. Formal ethical review was not required because the study involved no experimental intervention.}

\subsection{Measurement}

Our main independent variable is \texttt{Government distance}, a respondent--government distance measure based on party-closeness ratings.\footnote{Because \texttt{Government distance} is constructed from respondents' party-closeness ratings to governing parties, it already captures partisan orientation and its intensity in a continuous, coalition-specific way.}

Let $i$ index respondents and let $p \in G$ index parties in the governing coalition. Survey respondents rated their closeness to each parliamentary party on a $0$--$10$ scale. Let $C_{ip} \in [0,10]$ denote respondent $i$'s closeness to party $p$. Let $s_p$ be party $p$'s seat count in the \emph{Eduskunta} at the time of fieldwork,\footnote{KOK $=48$, PS $=46$, RKP $=9$, KD $=5$.} and define coalition seat weights
\begin{equation}
w_p \equiv \frac{s_p}{\sum_{q \in G} s_q}.
\label{eq:weights}
\end{equation}

Because of item nonresponse, we renormalize weights over the set of governing parties actually rated by respondent $i$:
\begin{equation}
\tilde w_{ip} \equiv
\frac{w_p \,\mathbbm{1}\!\bigl\{\text{$C_{ip}$ observed}\bigr\}}
{\sum_{q \in G} w_q \,\mathbbm{1}\!\bigl\{\text{$C_{iq}$ observed}\bigr\}}.
\label{eq:renorm}
\end{equation}

Seat-weighted coalition closeness is then
\begin{equation}
{\texttt{Government closeness}}_i \equiv \sum_{p \in G} \tilde w_{ip}\, C_{ip} \;\in\; [0,10].
\label{eq:govclose}
\end{equation}

We scale this quantity to $[0,1]$ and define the complementary distance index:
\begin{equation}
{\texttt{Government distance}}_i \equiv 1 - \frac{{\texttt{Government closeness}}_i}{10}
\;\in\; [0,1].
\label{eq:govdist}
\end{equation}
By construction, larger values of ${\texttt{Government distance}}_i$ indicate greater ideological distance from the governing coalition.

To assess whether the results depend on this particular aggregation rule, we also construct two conceptually adjacent distance measures. First, an \emph{unweighted} coalition proximity gives each governing party equal weight, abstracting from parliamentary strength and reducing dependence on the cabinet's seat distribution. Define
\[
\texttt{Government closeness (UW)}_i \;\equiv\;
\frac{\sum_{p\in G} C_{ip}\,\mathbbm{1}\!\bigl\{\text{$C_{ip}$ observed}\bigr\}}
     {\sum_{q\in G} \mathbbm{1}\!\bigl\{\text{$C_{iq}$ observed}\bigr\}}
\;\in\;[0,10],
\label{eq:govclose_u}
\tag{A1}
\]
with \texttt{NA} if no governing party was rated. The corresponding distance measure is
\begin{equation}
\texttt{Government distance (UW)}_i \;\equiv\;
1 - \frac{\texttt{Government closeness (UW)}_i}{10}
\;\in\;[0,1].
\label{eq:govdist_u}
\end{equation}

Second, a \emph{closest-party} distance measure captures the heuristic that respondents may anchor their evaluation on the governing party they feel closest to, and it is especially robust to selective nonresponse:
\begin{equation}
\texttt{Government distance (Closest)}_i \;\equiv\;
1 - \frac{\max_{p\in G}\, C_{ip}}{10}
\;\in\;[0,1],
\label{eq:govdist_min}
\end{equation}
set to \texttt{NA} when all $C_{ip}$ for $p\in G$ are missing.

Taken together, the seat-weighted (\autoref{eq:govdist}), unweighted (\autoref{eq:govdist_u}), and closest-party (\autoref{eq:govdist_min}) measures capture influence-weighted proximity to the governing bloc, equal-weight proximity across coalition parties, and a strongest-affinity anchor, respectively. We use all three in the empirical analysis. As shown below, they yield substantively similar patterns, which suggests that our findings do not hinge on a particular aggregation rule or treatment of item nonresponse.

\subsection{Estimation Strategy}

We estimate the association between support for technocratic delegation (\texttt{Technocracy}) and ideological distance from the governing coalition (\texttt{Government distance}) using a linear specification. Let $\texttt{Technocracy}_i$ denote respondent $i$'s response to the technocracy survey item and ${\texttt{Government distance}}_i$ the normalized index in \autoref{eq:govdist}.\footnote{We treat the $1$--$5$ outcome as approximately continuous; ordered models are reported as robustness checks in \autoref{tab:ologit-models} and yield substantively similar conclusions. The survey question asked (originally in Finnish): ``What do you think about the following statements? [...] Our country would work better if political decisions were left to independent, non-elected experts instead of politicians.'' The response options were ``Strongly disagree'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$techno5)[1])}), ``Somewhat disagree'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$techno5)[2])}), ``Neither agree nor disagree'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$techno5)[3])}), ``Somewhat agree'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$techno5)[4])}), and ``Totally agree'' (n=\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$techno5)[5])}).}

For exposition, we use the seat-weighted index as the primary measure because it most closely tracks the theoretical object of interest: proximity to the governing bloc as a policy-setting coalition. It also reduces noise from idiosyncratic ratings of very small coalition partners with limited bargaining influence. We then re-estimate all models using the unweighted and closest-party variants; the results are substantively unchanged (\autoref{tab:ols-models}). The baseline model is
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\texttt{Technocracy}_i \;=\;& \beta_0 \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_1\,\texttt{Government distance}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_2\,\texttt{Democratic satisfaction}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_3\,\texttt{Trust in politicians}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \boldsymbol{\gamma}'\,\mathbf{X}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \delta_{\text{region}(i)} \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \varepsilon_i \, ,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:model}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{X}_i$ includes education, age, and gender, and $\delta_{\text{region}(i)}$ are region fixed effects. Under the formal model's general expectation, the coefficient of interest, $\beta_1$, should be negative.

\subsection{Results}

\autoref{fig:pred} plots marginal-standardized (average) predictions of support for technocratic delegation across the full range of distance from the current Finnish Government.\footnote{The solid line is the point estimate and the band is the 95\% confidence interval.} The estimated effects are modest but substantively meaningful in a hard case such as Finland. Across all three panels---seat-weighted, unweighted, and closest-party---the relationship is monotonically negative: moving from full proximity to maximal distance from the Government lowers the predicted score from roughly 3.5 to about 2.8 on the 1--5 scale. The near-identical slope in the unweighted panel indicates that the pattern does not depend on coalition seat shares or renormalization, and the closest-party panel reproduces the same decline.

<<pred, fig.width=11, fig.height=4, out.width='\\textwidth', fig.cap='Average predicted: technocracy vs.\\ government distance (95\\% CIs).', echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=
print(pred_plot_3panel)

@

In light of our voter-choice framework, these estimates are consistent with a spatial mechanism in which expected policy under delegation depends on perceived government--expert alignment. When experts are perceived as tracking the incumbent coalition, delegation implies a policy closer to the government's position, so respondents farther from the government in ideological space are less likely to prefer delegation to the status quo. Substantively, the negative slope indicates that support for technocratic delegation is concentrated among citizens who are closer to the governing bloc, consistent with our claim that technocratic delegation is evaluated as ideologically valenced rather than uniformly attractive across the electorate.

Although the survey does not directly ask whether respondents perceive experts as ideologically biased, the gradient in \autoref{fig:pred} is unlikely to be a simple artifact of measurement or aggregation. The pattern suggests that at least a nontrivial share of respondents inferred some alignment between expert bodies and the right-leaning cabinet, which reduced willingness to delegate among those farthest from the government in ideological space. The near-parallel slopes across the seat-weighted, unweighted, and closest-party panels, together with ordered-logit estimates that treat the outcome as ordinal (\autoref{tab:ologit-models}), further suggest that the core association is not driven by a specific proximity measure or outcome scaling choice.


%At the same time, the results do not imply that Finnish voters uniformly view experts as politicized. A more plausible interpretation is heterogeneous inference within a high-trust environment: many respondents appear broadly trusting of expert institutions, while others---disproportionately those farther from the governing coalition---are more sensitive to who is empowered and who appoints them.


This aggregate pattern likely masks meaningful heterogeneity in how citizens evaluate expert governance. Recent work using conjoint experiments and latent class analysis identifies distinct citizen profiles with respect to alternative forms of representation: some respondents favor technocratic approaches while rejecting populist politicians, others combine populist and technocratic sentiments, and others prioritize party-democratic representation \parencite{Bertsou:2024}. In a multiparty context such as Finland, where coalition politics and consensus norms remain central, ideological camps may hold different conceptions of legitimate governance even when all claim to support democracy. Research on democratic conceptions suggests precisely this possibility: citizens can endorse democracy while attaching that label to quite different institutional arrangements \parencite{Bryan:2023}. Some respondents may emphasize efficiency and policy performance, making them more receptive to technocratic delegation; others may prioritize representation and accountability, making them more skeptical of unelected authority. Our interactive results below help clarify this heterogeneity: the distance penalty attenuates when experts are perceived as more independent, which suggests that electoral losers are not uniformly hostile to expertise but are specifically reluctant to delegate to experts they expect to advance the government's agenda. This pattern is consistent with broader work on conditional institutional support, in which commitment to democratic rules and independent institutions depends in part on whether those institutions are perceived as constraining or advantaging political opponents \parencite{Gessler:2025, van-der-Brug:2021}.

\paragraph{Perceived Government-Expert Alignment}

Because we do not directly observe whether respondents believe expert bodies are aligned with the government, we proxy perceived alignment using a relative trust differential between the Cabinet and a flagship expert institution, the Bank of Finland.\footnote{The survey question asked (originally in Finnish): ``How much do you trust or distrust the following? Please rate each on a scale of 0 to 10, where 1 is `I don't at all' and 10 is `I trust completely' [Bank of Finland].'' The distribution is: 0 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[1])}, 1 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[2])}, 2 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[3])}, 3 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[4])}, 4 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[5])}, 5 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[6])}, 6 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[7])}, 7 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[8])}, 8 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[9])}, 9 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[10])}, 10 = \Sexpr{as.numeric(table(dat.t$Q9_7)[11])}.}

The logic is comparative. Respondents who trust the Cabinet more than the Bank of Finland are more likely to infer that expert agencies will follow the government's lead; respondents who trust the Bank of Finland more are more likely to infer institutional independence. This proxy rests on a behavioral assumption: citizens understand that governments appoint senior officials, influence mandates, and shape institutional environments, and they use relative trust to infer likely control. On this view, higher trust in the Cabinet implies greater expected alignment of expert bodies with the government's program, whereas higher trust in the Bank of Finland implies greater expected insulation. The measure is therefore not a direct observation of perceived capture, but an indirect indicator of how respondents locate expert authority relative to elected government.

Formally, let $T_i^G$ denote trust in the current government ($0$--$10$) and $T_i^E$ trust in the Bank of Finland. Define the signed gap
\[
\texttt{Align}_i \equiv T_i^G - T_i^E.
\]
For exposition we map this to the unit interval and, for estimation, center it at the indifference point:
\[
\texttt{Align}^{01}_i \in [0,1], \qquad
\texttt{Align}^{01}_{i,c} \equiv \texttt{Align}^{01}_i - 0.5 \in [-0.5,0.5].
\]

<<pred.4, fig.width=6, fig.height=4, out.width='0.65\\textwidth', fig.cap='Interactive OLS hypothesis: Technocracy $\\times$ Government distance moderated by Gov-Expert trust gap', fig.pos='H', echo=FALSE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE>>=

print(pint)

@

By construction, $\texttt{Align}^{01}_{i,c}=0$ indicates approximate indifference ($T_i^G \approx T_i^E$); positive values indicate a government-over-experts premium ($T_i^G>T_i^E$), and negative values indicate an experts-over-government premium ($T_i^E>T_i^G$). Using the gap rather than the levels $T_i^G$ and $T_i^E$ reduces sensitivity to response-style differences (e.g., $(8,7)$ and $(2,1)$ encode the same comparative orientation) and centers the analysis on perceived alignment rather than absolute institutional trust.

We estimate
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\texttt{Technocracy}_i \;=\;& \beta_0 \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_1\,\texttt{Government distance}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_2\,\texttt{Align}^{01}_{i,c} \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \beta_3\,\bigl(\texttt{Government distance}_i \times \texttt{Align}^{01}_{i,c}\bigr) \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \boldsymbol{\gamma}'\,\mathbf{X}_i \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \delta_{\text{region}(i)} \\[2pt]
&\;+\; \varepsilon_i \, ,
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:model-interaction}
\end{equation}

and plot marginal predictions at $\texttt{Align}^{01}_{i,c} \in \{-0.25,\,0,\,+0.25\}$, labeled in the legend as ``Experts trusted'' (negative gap), ``Indifferent'' ($0$), and ``Government trusted'' (positive gap).\footnote{Following \textcite[73]{Brambor2006}, we interpret the interaction through marginal effects rather than coefficient signs in the regression table (\autoref{tab:interact-models}).}

\autoref{fig:pred.4} supports the mechanism implied by the theory. Among respondents who trust the Government more than the Bank of Finland, the predicted relationship between \texttt{Government distance} and support for technocratic delegation is clearly negative: the farther respondents are from the Government, the less they support delegation to experts. Among respondents who are roughly indifferent, the slope is much flatter. Among respondents who trust the Bank of Finland more than the Government, the slope becomes slightly positive. Substantively, ideological distance depresses support for technocratic delegation primarily when respondents expect experts to follow the Government's lead; when experts are perceived as more independent, that distance penalty attenuates and may even reverse slightly. This is the core result of the paper. It suggests that losers' consent to technocratic delegation is conditional on perceived alignment and that ideological distance operates through inferred institutional positioning rather than as a uniform aversion to expertise.

\section{Discussion and Limitations}

This study argues that citizens evaluate technocratic delegation through an ideologically valenced lens. We formalize delegation as a spatial comparison between expected policy under elected--politician control and expected policy under expert rule, where the latter depends on perceived government--expert alignment. The model yields two central implications: support for technocratic delegation should decline with ideological distance from government when experts are perceived as aligned with incumbents, and this distance penalty should attenuate when experts are perceived as more neutral. Using a novel survey of Finnish adults, we find evidence consistent with both implications. Across multiple operationalizations of government distance and across linear and ordered-logit models, support for technocratic delegation declines monotonically as respondents move farther from the governing coalition. This negative association is then conditioned by perceived alignment: it is strongest among respondents who trust the Government more than the Bank of Finland and weakens substantially among respondents who trust the Bank of Finland more.

Finland is a particularly demanding setting for this argument. High institutional trust, relatively low levels of polarization by comparative standards, and strong traditions of consensus-building should all make expert authority comparatively legitimate. The fact that we still observe ideologically conditional support for delegation suggests that the mechanism is not confined to low-trust or highly conflictual systems. At the same time, this does not imply that Finnish citizens broadly perceive experts as politicized. The evidence instead suggests heterogeneity within a high-trust polity: many respondents appear willing to support technocratic delegation, but support becomes conditional among those who infer that expert institutions align with the governing coalition. In that sense, the Finnish case is informative precisely because it sharpens the contrast between baseline trust in expertise and conditional withdrawal of support when alignment is inferred.

The results also speak to a broader debate about whether opposition to institutional delegation reflects principled commitments or partisan strategy. One interpretation is consistent with our spatial model: respondents far from the Government oppose delegation because they expect delegated policy to track the incumbent coalition. A second interpretation emphasizes what recent scholarship labels \enquote{democratic hypocrisy}, namely the instrumental endorsement of democratic norms and institutional constraints when they disadvantage the out-party and their devaluation when they empower political opponents \parencite{McCoy:2020}. These mechanisms are not mutually exclusive. Indeed, the two may reinforce one another. If respondents infer that experts are aligned with incumbents, an expected policy loss and an institutional advantage for opponents might point in the same direction. This possibility is especially plausible in multiparty contexts such as Finland, where affective polarization can organize voters into \enquote{affective blocs} that generate layered patterns of affinity and hostility across several parties rather than a simple binary divide \parencite{Kekkonen:2021}. The interaction results suggest that perceived alignment is a key mediator, but future work should incorporate direct measures of partisan animus and out-group threat to better distinguish policy-based objections from identity-based motivated reasoning \parencite{Simonovits:2022}.

Our findings also have implications for institutional design. If support for technocratic delegation depends on whether citizens perceive experts as aligned with incumbents, then formal independence is necessary but not sufficient. What matters politically is not only \emph{de jure} insulation but also the credibility of that insulation in the eyes of citizens. Comparative work on the appointment of judges, central bankers, prosecutors, and regulatory officials suggests that institutional features such as supermajority appointment rules, fixed non-renewable terms, transparent selection criteria, and involvement of multiple nomination bodies can strengthen both formal independence and public confidence \parencite{Miliuviene:2024}. In polarized contexts, the public-facing features of appointment design may be especially important. When appointments appear opaque, incumbent-dominated, or politically timed, electoral losers have reasons to infer alignment and to oppose delegation. By contrast, transparent and visibly cross-partisan procedures can reduce such inferences and improve the legitimacy of unelected institutions. This point connects to broader work on deliberation and institutional legitimacy: the communicative and procedural visibility of independence may matter nearly as much as legal protections on paper \parencite{Ganuza:2020}. %Finland's comparatively strong baseline trust in expert institutions may itself reflect this combination of formal design and visible consensus-oriented governance.

Several limitations remain. First, our key moderator---the trust differential between the Government and the Bank of Finland---is a proxy for perceived alignment, not a direct measure of whether respondents believe experts are government-aligned. The fact that the interaction behaves as the theory predicts provides suggestive construct validity, but the proxy may also absorb incumbency approval, generalized regime affect, or broader institutional sentiment. Second, the design is observational and cross-sectional. Ideological distance and the trust differential may both be shaped by latent predispositions, including anti-elitism, diffuse political trust, or stable partisan identities. The associations we document are therefore consistent with the theory but do not establish causal effects.

More generally, the empirical analysis tests the formal model at the level of its broad implications rather than each of its formal objects or comparative statics. Although the evidence is consistent with the model's central prediction that perceived government--expert alignment conditions the effect of ideological distance on support for technocratic delegation, future research should collect direct measures of the status quo policy baseline, perceived expert location, and institutional alignment, and use experimental designs to test the model's finer-grained comparative statics more directly.

Third, our distance measure relies on self-reported party-closeness ratings and seat-share weights as a proxy for influence within the governing coalition. Although the results replicate with unweighted and closest-party variants, measurement error in party closeness or imperfect correspondence between seat shares and perceived agenda power could still affect estimates. Fourth, the technocracy outcome is a single ordered item. While ordered-logit robustness checks yield substantively similar conclusions, single-item measures remain vulnerable to wording effects and respondent-specific scale use. Fifth, although Finland is a valuable hard case, external validity remains an open question. The same mechanism may be stronger in settings with lower institutional trust or more visible politicization of expert bodies, but it may also interact with country-specific institutional histories and patterns of party competition. Finally, our analyses concern attitudes rather than behavior. We do not directly observe whether conditional support for technocratic delegation translates into electoral choices, support for institutional reform, or tolerance for weakening expert agencies.

These limitations also define the next steps. Future surveys should include direct measures of perceived expert alignment, appointment credibility, and perceived institutional capture. Experimental designs could randomize appointment procedures (e.g., partisan appointment vs.\ supermajority appointment), transparency, and ideological cues to identify how citizens infer alignment and when those inferences affect support for delegation. Panel designs around cabinet reshuffles, high-salience appointments, or conflicts between governments and independent agencies would further improve causal leverage. Comparative work is also needed. A cross-national design could test whether the negative effect of government distance on support for technocratic delegation intensifies where expert politicization is more salient and accountability concerns are more acute. Within-country analyses could examine whether the mechanism varies across parties, regions, or levels of political sophistication. Finally, linking these attitudes to behavior---support for institutional reform, willingness to delegate in specific policy domains, or tolerance for constraining expert agencies---would clarify the political consequences of ideologically valenced technocratic delegation.

Taken together, the evidence suggests a broader point about democratic stability. Institutions designed to insulate policymaking from partisan conflict can support democratic governance only when they are perceived as credibly independent. When electoral losers infer that expert institutions are aligned with incumbents, support for delegation declines, even in a high-trust democracy. The challenge is therefore not only to design independent institutions, but also to sustain the cross-partisan legitimacy that makes delegation politically acceptable.


